<emphasis bold="true" box="[178,660,990,1012]" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397">
5.2.14. The 
<taxonomicName box="[303,507,990,1012]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scaphisoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pictum">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[303,507,990,1012]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397">Scaphisoma pictum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="58" pageNumber="1397" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="58.[178,1085,1032,1201]" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397">
Members of the group share with the Palaearctic 
<emphasis box="[679,787,1032,1053]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397">S. assimile</emphasis>
Erichson, 1845 and its allied species a bilobed apical process of the median lobe, but usually differ drastically by the broadly lobed parameres. The elytra, unlike those in members of the 
<emphasis box="[900,1011,1091,1112]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397">S. assimile</emphasis>
group, lack basal striae (
<bibRefCitation author="LOBL I." box="[373,567,1119,1142]" journalOrPublisher="Revue suisse Zool" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397" pagination="937 - 1006" part="78" refString="LOBL I. (1971 b): Scaphidiidae von Ceylon (Coleoptera). - Revue suisse Zool. 78: 937 - 1006." title="Scaphidiidae von Ceylon (Coleoptera)" type="journal article" year="1971" yearSuffix="b">LÖBL 1971b: 962</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[591,812,1120,1142]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397">
<taxonomicName box="[591,713,1120,1141]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Scaphisoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scaphisoma</taxonomicName>
cuyunon
</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis box="[831,1004,1120,1141]" italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397">S. hexameroides</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="58" pageNumber="1397">S. iridescens</emphasis>
which have basally broadened but not lobed parameres are tentatively placed in this group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
